<paragraph blockId="68.[227,348,441,467]" box="[227,348,441,467]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,348,441,467]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,348,441,467]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Diagnosis</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="68.[226,1439,489,587]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">OL/OH = 1.03–1.33, OsL/CaL = 0.83–1.20. Circular otoliths with small, pointed but well-developed rostrum and antirostrum. Shape of posterior rim varies markedly among specimens. Sulcus well divided into ostium and cauda.</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="68.[227,362,628,654]" box="[227,362,628,654]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">
<heading bold="true" box="[227,362,628,654]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="68" pageNumber="69" reason="3">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[227,362,628,654]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">Etymology</emphasis>
</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="68.[227,1119,675,702]" box="[227,1119,675,702]" pageId="68" pageNumber="69">The name alludes to the considerable intraspecific variability of the otoliths.</paragraph>
